Doing some research on the iOS video player and how much can we customize it and wether it will fit our needs or not, this includes custom shaped buttons (to be used as hotspots) and gestures support.

Getting up to speed with new iOS version and the newest SDK, studying the new features and how they might help us with the project, and wether we should use them or not, Exploring the options we have for Gestures
Doing project estimates, analyzing piece by piece and trying to figure out the best approach for each, doing a bit of research if needed to estimate as accurate as possible

Implementing an AVFoundation based video player, using the m4v file included in the old prototype, adding support for playback and implementing hotspots on top of each continent, wiring everything together in order to have a fully functional demo for tomorrow.

Setting up the project, catching up and doing some research on AVFoundation and the way it works in iOS 4.3, doing research on what's the best way to implement hotspots / overlays in order to wisely manage memory and resources.
Meetings with Matthew and the customer, discussing where to start and prioritizing the first deliverables, planing ahead the first week of work. Exchanging contact data.

Implementing the notification system that deals with all the messaging back and forth from and to different controls, doing some more research on how to handle playback rates in the AVFoundation's AVPlayer

Wiring the playback speed control, now we provide a PopOver control with a nested tableview and several playback speed options (right now .5X, 1X, 3X, 5X and 10X), this master control affects all video players in the application along with the master counter of months and years (and later the scrubber bar as well).

Generating Dynamic overlays, yesterday's implementation of the AVFoundation-based movie player had "hardcoded" shapes in order to detect clicks over continents, this was obviously not going to work once we resize the movie player (e.g. to add the thermometer view) since the overlays would not match the continents in the video anymore. Now the Overlay position and size are being determined dynamically.

Decoupling the video player from the main ViewController, due to yesterday's experiments, the videoplayer was part of the main ViewController, which wasn't good for several reasons, in order to encapsulate all it's functionality and being able to reuse it in other pieces, I had to abstract it to it's own ViewController
Daily scrum meeting with Matthew, demoing the progress so far, showing the simple AVPlayer and playback, along with how the "hardcoded" custom shaped overlays work
Video editing the main video so that we can have different test videos. Daily call with Matthew, composing the email report that was sent to the customer.
Implementing gestures recognition, so that the user can pinch-zoom the continent video in and out, adding animations to the resize events of each video player.

Doing Sync tests, testing pre-buffering several videos at the same time and switching them, increasing and decreasing playback speed, resizing video views at runtime, trying to find a way to send a sync signal every n seconds so that all video players in memory can be synchronized at once.

Changing the way the videoplayer is wired to the month and year counter, now we use a TimeObserver that gets triggered every 1/12th of a played second, which means that even if the playback speed is not 1X, the months and years counter still gets notified properly

Analyzing the app with instruments, doing a lot of debugging and changes to improve memory management, fixing several memory leaks that were introduced after many of the tests I made to keep videos and displays synchronized. Refactoring some other pieces to increase performance.

After doing research, I decided to refactor the way the different video players are currently handled, using static instances for each model (player itself) and corresponding UIViewControllers to improve overall performance and keeping all of them always on sync. I also decided to replace the old sync system (a timed notification) with something a lot more optimized

Video Synchronization: Trying different approaches to keep multiple videos synchronized, trying some of the suggestions that Nick made earlier this morning, doing some research on how framerate works and how the AV player handles it internally.
Call with Matt and Nick, talking about the approaches taken so far to do video synchronization and demonstrating the progress so far.

Fixing a bug that was causing a memory warning to be sent to the main view controller, deallocating controls that were not used anymore and improving memory handling overall. Testing final results of the day and found stability was improved, but still each player would consume 20MB of ram.

Debugging synchronization, due to the latest changes on how the video player instances are kept, the synchronization between videos was lost, changing the way we observe time changes and how those are messaged to other video players.

Refactoring the video handling again, using lazy loading initialization and fixing several memory leaks, debugging issues that were found while running the app on the actual hardware, making sure each instance is always preserved for later usage.
Phone call with Matthew, talking about performance and other approaches (generating the animation on a Google Map view instead of videos)

Walking Stuardo through the app, making sure he understands all the concepts and goals, and the approaches currently being taken, what has been done and what is to be done, and what pieces are going to be in his plate soon.

After managing to achieve a low enough memory foot print in the video playback part, I had to rewrite the synchronizing piece, which was causing a noticeable delay whenever the current video item would be switched. (Entry 2 of 2)

After managing to achieve a low enough memory foot print in the video playback part, I had to rewrite the synchronizing piece, which was causing a noticeable delay whenever the current video item would be switched. (Entry 1 of 2)

Changing once again the way video player memory is handled, adding one single video player this time and several static, lazy loaded video items that are being switched at runtime, lowering the memory footprint to a total of 20MB of RAM for all the video players. (Entry 2 of 2)

Changing once again the way video player memory is handled, adding one single video player this time and several static, lazy loaded video items that are being switched at runtime, lowering the memory footprint to a total of 20MB of RAM for all the video players. (Entry 1 of 2)

Adding the scrubber bar, wiring it to the current playback time observer and animating it so that it moves to the right at the same rate the movie is being played. Detecting touches on the time marker (arrow) and now supporting drag and drop, wiring it to the master playback control so that upon releasing it at an X location (drop) we could calculate a proper CMTime and make the video player SeekTo that particular time. (Entry 2 of 2)

Now that the video playing part has both a low memory footprint and seamless synchronization, I had to fix the part that measures video playback progress and updates the months and year counters, the new approach was to read the current playback time (easier now that we only have one video player across the entire app) rather than relaying on the AVPlayer's internal timeObserver. (Entry 2 of 2)

Modifying the way the video player behaves after successfully playing a video, doing some memory cleanup and restarting the playback point to zero, properly managing the time observer that updates the month and year counters and also properly handling the scrubber marker drag and drop event (temporarily stoping the timer to avoid glitches etc)

Fixing the pinch zoom on the video player object, refactoring the video player with a UIViewController instead of the regular UIView we had in order to also support panning, setting maximum zoom levels.

After coding the range selection logic, I also added support to loop video playback within that range, which means that after the user adds a range in the scrubber bar, the video playback loops within such range and continues like that until the user clears the range with the "Turn off range" button.

Adding support for drawing a hidden UIImageView that contains the image that will later be used as the "selected range" on the scrubber bar, the overlapped image is being drawn with a pinch gesture and the event handler automatically calculates the proper frame (origin and size) of the selection. (Entry 2 of 2)
